This paper primarily focuses on facial analysis applications, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) category. The paper proposes a novel method for simultaneously super-resolving and frontalizing tiny non-frontal face images, which involves the use of deep learning techniques and generative adversarial networks (GANs), indicating a possible fit for artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) categories. The paper also mentions the use of discriminators to capture both global and detailed facial characteristics, which could potentially fall under multimedia (cs.MM) and graphics (cs.GR) categories.
